<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="45a061f8-420e-5add-b021-75032bc2fad2" activityNameId="5a47d958-8c0e-4a04-b590-258f47c25bad" parentActivityId="2ec6550d-ae17-4a97-9a5d-8f184edd85d9" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">coke production, wet quenching</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">CWQ</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">Activity starts with the reception of coal at plant-site.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the supply of 1 kg of coke, considering the by-product recovery, to the chinese and global market. Transport is not included.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This multioutput-process represents the supply of coke by using the wet quenching (CWQ) technology, producing coal gas, coal tar, sulfur and benzene as a byproduct whithin the geography of China.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset is based on the article “Life cycle environmental performance of by-product coke production in China” from Liu, X. and Yuan, Z. (2016).</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="3aa0f2c5-1d26-4f98-8c2c-7406d4b7f2ae">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">1910:Manufacture of coke oven products</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0c40fa1e-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">CN</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Domestic coking coal reserves for coke production are very rich</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">and centrally distributed in Shanxi, Anhui and Shandong Provinces,</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">which accounted for approximately 70% of the Chinese total coking</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">coal resources (Fan, W.T., 2005. Chinese Coking Coal Resources, Production and Quality. China National Coal Association, Beijing, China.) By that it is assumed for the entire country.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Wet quenching plays a significant role in the production of coke and is the traditional procedure. In the coke-making process, coal is heated in an oxygen-depleted environment to remove volatile components and produce coke. Wet quenching is employed to rapidly cool down the hot coke and stabilize its structure. The coke is typically transferred to a quenching tower, where it comes into contact with water sprays or is submerged in water. This immediate cooling prevents the coke from further reacting with oxygen, which could result in its combustion. Additionally, wet quenching helps to harden and strengthen the coke, making it more suitable for transportation and handling.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2013-01-01" endDate="2024-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true"/>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
