    <modellingAndValidation>
      <representativeness systemModelId="290c1f85-4cc4-4fa1-b0c8-2cb7f4276dce">
        <systemModelName xml:lang="en">Allocation, cut-off by classification</systemModelName>
        <samplingProcedure xml:lang="en">Bases on a study that compiles LCI data pertaining to most of the life cycle stages of "byproduct" coke production through site-specific interviews and measurements. Nevertheless, for upstream processes like raw material extraction, production, transportation, and certain processes lacking emission data, it relies on background information from commercial inventory databases, expert estimations, and published literature. The majority of the data concerning coke production is sourced from medium-sized coke production enterprises located in Shanxi Province and Jiangsu Province, China, with annual production capacities ranging from 0.7 to 1 million tons of metallurgical coke.
The study's system boundaries encompass several stages, including raw material acquisition, on-site coal preparation, thermal distillation, coke handling and storage, and by-product recovery. Air pollutants generated during charging, pushing, quenching, coke screening, and combustion are collected using air pollution control devices (APCDs).
The authors primarily focus on-site air emissions and water pollutants, as all solid wastes generated during production are collected and reintegrated with coals. Emissions of conventional air pollutants such as PM, SO2, and NO2 are calculated based on on-site environmental monitoring data. CO2, CH4, and CO emissions are derived from the Ecoinvent Database v2.2.

</samplingProcedure>
        <extrapolations xml:lang="en">This dataset is built based on the results of the study by Liu and Yuan (2016). For more information, please see the published source.</extrapolations>
      </representativeness>
